I. Motivation

Many graduate students at CSU perform designed experiments to understand causation. We often turn to ANOVAs or ANCOVAs to analyze the effects of treatments in these experiments. The Bayesian methods you have learned in this class can be usefully applied to these problems. We often need the Bayesian approach to account for errors in reponses, to deal with group level effects, and, as illustrated here, to deal with spatial autocorrelation. This lab provides illustrates the analysis of a designed experiment with a data model for an unobserved state and continuous spatial depdence in the data.

II. Problem

A central goal in ecology is to understand the factors that promote colonization of founding populations (Mayr 1965, MacArthur & Wilson 1967). For over a decade, propagule pressure, or the number of individuals in a founding group, has been considered a null hypothesis for predicting colonization success (Lockwood et al. 2005, Simberloff 2009). However, there is accumulating evidence that intraspecific diversity within a founding group drives the positive relationship between propagule pressure and colonization success, as diversity increases with increasing propagule pressure from a pure probability standpoint (Ahlroth et al. 2003, Lockwood et al. 2005, Elam et al. 2007).

We will analyze the importance of source diversity on the colonization success of Bromus tectorum (cheatgrass) founding populations in a common garden in Colorado. An experiment manipulated the number of geographically distinct sources represented in experimental populations of 32 cheatgrass seeds (5 levels of diversity: 1, 2, 4, 8, 16 sources represented; hereafter: source diversity). The objective of the experiment was to determine if the strength of the diversity effect would vary if seeds were pre-adapted to the common garden. To do this, experimental plots were composed of seeds from Colorado or Nevada (hereafter: source region) across all diversity treatments; Colorado representing the pre-adapted treatment and Nevada the unadapted one.

III. Preliminaries

We need to compose two separate models to understand the effect of source diversity and source region on the colonization success of our experimental populations. The response variable of interest is the number of seeds produced, which will give us an idea of how many individuals could establish in the following generation. Unfortunately, we only have data on the total seed biomass because there were far too many seeds to count. Thus, the first model we need to construct is a calibration model explaining the relationship between seed count and seed weight. We will then use parameters from this model to inform priors in our Bayesian regression model assessing the importance of source region and diversity on colonization success (number of seeds produced per population).

You will need install the packages ade4 and matrixStats.

IV. Calibration model

To inform the calibration model, we counted and weighed seeds from a subset of experimental plots (see calibration data set).

  1. We have written the likelihood for the relationship between seed count and seed weight, where seed weight is the response of interest. As seed weight can only be positive, it is lognormally distributed. We assume a linear relationship between seed weight and seed count with an intercept that crosses zero (i.e. there is no intercept parameter, just a slope).

log(wi)normal(log(cxc,i),2c)log(wi)normal(log(cxc,i),c2)

model{
  
  ### priors 
  tau ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  alpha ~ dnorm(0, 1e-4)

  # derived quantities
  sd2 <- 1 / tau
  
  ### likelihood

  # because we are taking the log of the product alpha*x_ct, we need to restrict values to be       
  # positive. by looping through all values and choosing the maximum between a very small number positive   
  # number and each alpha*x_c[i], we restrict all values to be non-zero and positive

   for (i in 1:n){
     mu[i] <- max(1e-10, x_ct[i] * alpha)
   }
  
  # remember, y_lnwt is already log-transformed
  for (i in 1:n){
    y_lnwt[i] ~ dnorm(log(mu[i]), tau)
  }
  
  
  }# end model
    
",fill=TRUE)

}

  2. In the hierarchical model below, we will parameterize cc and cc using an informed gamma prior using values from this calibration experiment. Write an R function using the means and standard deviations of the marginal posterior distributions of cc and cc found here, to calculate the shape and rate parameters of a gamma distribution. Save these as objects you will need them for the next model.
# extract mean and sd of alpha
mu_alpha <- mean(zj.cal$alpha) 
sd_alpha <- sd(zj.cal$alpha) 

mu_tau <- mean(zj.cal$tau) 
sd_tau <- sd(zj.cal$tau) 

# moment-matching for informed prior
gamma<- function (mn, sd){
  a = mn ^2 / sd^2
  b= mn / sd^2
  return(c(a, b))
}

alpha_prior <-gamma(mu_alpha, sd_alpha)
# 2614.373 10054.346

tau_prior <- gamma(mu_tau, sd_tau)
# 17.183387  0.211654

V. Hierarchical model

We are interested in how source diversity and source region influence the population-level production of cheatgrass seeds. The observed data, yiyi, are the seed biomass of each experimental population. We want to understand how the number of seeds produced per population responds to the diversity treatment, and their interaction.

We have the following design matrix: 1. Column one contains 1s. 2. Column two contains diversity of plot ii (1, 2, 4, 8, or 16). 3. Column three contains the region for plot ii (1 if Nevada and 0 otherwise) 4 Column 4 is the product of diversity and region.

The response, yiyi is the observed count in plot ii divided by 100, i.e. the units of yy are 100s of seeds. You may reasonably treat counts as a continuous random variable because the observations in each plot number in the 10,000s. Compose a deterministic model that includes an intercept and the effects of diversity, region, and their interaction.

  1. Draw a DAG and write the posterior and joint distribution for the observed and unobserved quantities. Your model will include:
  • A data model relating the observed biomass to unobserved seed counts.
  • A process model that relates counts, to the parameters in the deterministic model and the design matrix. Assume that there is continuous spatial dependence among the plots that must be modeled. You may assume that unstructured variance = 0 because there is no measurement error or fine-scaled heterogeneity at the plot scale.
x,y[,2p,,,2cy]log(yi)log(z)=2unstrI2stre(Di,j)i=1n[yizi,2c][zX,][,2p,2c,]normal(log(czi),2c)multivariate normal(log(X),)with appropriate priors on parametersx,y=2unstrIstr2e(Di,j)[,p2,,,c2y]i=1n[yizi,c2][zX,][,p2,c2,]log(yi)normal(log(czi),c2)log(z)multivariate normal(log(X),)with appropriate priors on parameters
  1. Rather than blindly accept that data points are spatially autocorrelated, you should run a Mantel Test before you build your model to discover that there may be autocorrelation that must be accounted for. To do this, first, create a distance matrix using the dist() function in R. The only argument you will need to provide is two joined columns of east and north from the main data set (these represent distances east and north from a corner of the common garden). Then create a second matrix using the observed seed biomass data, seeds. Inspect the matrices using as.matrix(). Use the mantel.rtest() function in the ade4 library (you will need to install and load this) to test for spatial autocorreltation in the data. Remember, however, that it is spatial autocorrelation in the residuals that we must be concerned about to assure that iid assumptions are met. It may be that your deterministic model sufficeintly accounts for variation in responses over space over space such that residuals are not spatially structured.

What do these matrices represent? What is this test actually doing? Interpret your results.

library(ade4)
Mantel <- mantel.rtest(pop.dists, seeds.dists)

The first matrix looks at the distance between plots in the common garden (differences in values of east and north), while the second matrix looks at the difference in values of seed biomass). The Mantel test determines if there is a correlation between distance between plots and differences in seed biomass measurements between plots. A p-value less than 0.05 rejects the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between the two matrices and the value r reported represents the correlation. Here, we can reject the null and suggest that there is spatial auto-correlation with a correlation of r = 0.1983423.

Remember that Bayesians dont mix freuquentist with Bayesian analyses in the same paper. However, the Mantel test is a convenient way to evaluate if auto-correlation exists. An alternative would be to plot a semivariogram of the data, i.e, the semivariance vs the distance. This can be done without computing residuals using the plot function in the geoR package.

The covariance matrix in the process model will use the first distance matrix you created (structured variance) and an identity matrix multiplied by a separate variance component (unstructured variance), DD, such that

x,y=2unstrI+2stre(Dx,y)x,y=unstr2I+str2e(Dx,y)

Now lets put it all together. We have a likelihood relating the observed biomass data, yiyi, to the latent variable of seed number (in hundreds of seeds), zizi, that is parameterized using information from the calibration experiment. Seed number can be explained by a regression model using covariates of source diversity, source region, and their interaction, where observations of seed number covary based on their location in the common garden.

We will provide you will initial values to guide you in setting up the full model.

  1. Build and fit the hierarchical model to the experimental data in JAGS. We highly suggest using a small number of iterations as you are getting started with this model (it took 5 minutes to initialize, update, and make coda samples using n.adapt = 250, n.update = 500, n.iter = 1000). Once you get the model running with results that seem reasonable, then you can up your iterations. Some hints:
  • First, fit the model aspatially (no structured variance)
  • You will need to use dmvnorm() for the distribution of zz. Rather than looping over i values of zz, keep the mean and response as a vector. As with dnorm(), the variance component needs to be in the form of precision. To do this, take the inverse of your covariance matrix using inverse().
  • Create an object for the sum of your covariates multiplied by their respective s. We can call this vector uu and can create it using matrix multiplication in JAGS: u=Xu=X %*% .
  • You might need to restrict values to be greater than zero before they pass through a log() argument. Use the trick in the calibration model above to do this.
  • Keep zz log-transformed throughout the model. Remember than log(a*b) = log(a) + log(b). This should help in the likelihood.

As always, include code for posterior predictive checks.

{
sink("brte_model_jags.R")
cat("
 model{
  ## priors
  ## spatial priors 
  # COMMENT OUT FOR ASPATIAL MODEL
  tau.p.str ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2.p.str <- 1 / tau.p.str
  phi ~ dunif(1e-10, 5)
  
  # aspatial priors
  tau.p.unstr ~ dgamma(0.001, 0.001)
  sigma2.p.unstr <- 1/tau.p.unstr
  for(i in 1:p){
     beta[i]~dnorm(0,0.0001)
   }
   
  # informed priors
   tau.c  ~ dgamma(tau_prior[1], tau_prior[2])
   alpha.c ~ dgamma(alpha_prior[1], alpha_prior[2])
  

  ## create covariance matrix
  # account for spatial autocorrelation using a covariance matrix specified by
  # distance matrix (D), structured variance (sigma.p.str^2), and Matern variable (phi)
  # COMMENT OUT FOR ASPATIAL MODEL
   
   for(i in 1:n){
     for(j in 1:n){
       Cov.mat[i,j]<-sigma2.p.str*exp(-D[i,j]/phi)
     }
   }
   
  # Define identity matrix for sigma.p.unstr
    Id.mat <- Id * sigma2.p.unstr 

  # invert covariance matrix to obtain precision matrix (use in multivariate normal)
   
   Prec.mat <- inverse(Cov.mat + Id.mat)# COMMENT OUT FOR ASPATIAL MODEL
  # Prec.mat <- inverse(Id.mat)
   
  # mean number of seeds governed by beta priors and covariates
    mu <- X%*%beta
  
  # restrict mu to be positive (or you could exponentiate)
   for (i in 1:n){
     mu.pos[i]<- max(0.00000001, mu[i])
   }
   
  # multivariate lognormal (all positive values of seed number) with precision matrix
   lnz ~ dmnorm(log(mu.pos), Prec.mat)
   
  # likelihood (data conditioned on log(alpha.c*z[i]) which is the same as
  # log(alpha.c) + log(z[i])
    for (i in 1:n){
      y[i] ~ dnorm(log(alpha.c) + lnz[i], tau.c)
      y.new[i] ~ dnorm(log(alpha.c) + lnz[i], tau.c)
      
      # squared residuals for model fit
      sq.y[i] <- (y[i] - (log(alpha.c) + lnz[i])) ^ 2
      sq.ynew[i] <- (y.new[i] - (log(alpha.c) + lnz[i])) ^ 2
    }
      # posterior predictive check
   
      # sum of squared residuals (from above) for model fit
      sumsq.y <- sum(sq.y[])
      sumsq.ynew <- sum(sq.ynew[])
      p.sumsq <- step(sumsq.ynew - sumsq.y)
      
 }
",fill=TRUE)
sink()
}

As diversity increases, colonization success (i.e. the number of seeds produced per plot) increases. Source region (CO vs. NV) does not influence colonization success. The positive effect of diversity does not differ depending on source region.

  1. Make a graph with distance on the x-axis as covariance on the y-axis, using the exponential distance equation for which we used to create the covariance matrix. Plot the mean with 95% credible intervals. What does this tell you about the spatial autocorrelation if plots were 0.75m apart in the common garden?
distance <- seq(0, 20, 0.5)
covar <- function(phi, d, sigma.p.str){
  cov <- sigma.p.str^2 * exp(-d / phi)
  return(cov)
}

y <- matrix(nrow = length(zj.hier$phi), ncol = length(distance))

for (i in 1:length(zj.hier$phi)){
  y[i,] <- covar(phi = zj.hier$phi[i], d = distance, sigma.p.str = 1/zj.hier$tau.p.str[i])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(distance, colMeans(y), type = "l", ylab = "covariance")
library(matrixStats)
ci <- colQuantiles(y, probs = c(0.025, 0.975))
lines(distance, ci[,1], col = "red", lty = "dashed")
lines(distance, ci[,2], col = "red", lty = "dashed")

Plots that are less than 10 meters apart covary somewhat. Plots that are within ~4 meters of each other covary considerably.
